				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If someone does something wrong to you (on blue server), you'll ask them to stop. If they do not, then, well you're stuffed, because no GM will show up as you say, leaving the only other means to stop that person being an ILLEGAL action, which I do not condone, but maybe you do.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Mines actually purple, but it really is nothing more than a fancy blue server.
<br />

<br />
Ya pretty much have to deal with it, me i'm pretty easy going, i've spent enough time being frustrated in game and otherwise not to make fuss about some asshat causing players grief in a zone. Rep usually means a lot on blue servers because it's our only defense, we bar them from groups, raids, etc. You can only go so far in game w/o them. It's not as fast acting as the system you describe on Sullon, but it works. Most everybody else just chooses to whine and complain that it's not right, and that theres no GM to give them a band-aid.
<br />

<br />
I don't condone illegal actions to end any situation, or begin one for that matter. For me if there is a nuiescence in the zone that I can't avoid with /ignore i'm a capable Beast and can go somewhere else. Most people on the RP server understand if your going to start something you best be ready to accept the duel your instigate, the RP server though seems to run with a bit more mature crowd that the standard blue i played on before, but we still have our jerks.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Calling someone names doesnt really resolve the issue though does it? However killing them by LEGAL means does. Which can only be done on PVP servers.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> I was more or less reffering to those that can't seem to handle thier temper and do things that are not legal courses of actions and then receiving the flames later.
<br />

<br />
I've personally never been part of anyone situation that has commited those kind of acts, but i've been on the receiving end a few times. It can be frustrating, especially if no CSR reps are available(which is sadly about 90% of the time).Though if you going to be in a contested area I guess you have to expect competition. Nobody really likes having thier raid trained because some other greedy bunch decides they want it tho. I wouldn't mind the PvP server again, but as I tended to solo a lot I lost intrest when someone decided they just wanted to show up and take a camp by force. It may be a great way to solve issues, but a lot of times it causes issues as well.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If you act like a criminal, you become a criminal and get the reputation that comes with it. If a known person who trains people for laughs comes into my zone, I will kill him first rather than risk him training me later. This is the age of pre-emptive strieks afterall. The "eye for an eye" comment might eb true in R/L, but in EQ people just respawn and start again, there is an infinite supply of "eyes"</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I can see the logic in that, I guess it's more of a personal view, I just was never a big fan of reciprocative punishment. You grief me so I grief you to me really was nothing more than tug-o-grief. But then as I've told people so many times and myself as well, it's just a game, we shouldn't take it so seriously, goddess knows i've gone through my fair share of eyes <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Very Happy" border="0" /><br />_________________<br /><IMG SRC="http://members.cox.net/drezzttp/KurPhoto2.gif" WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=144 BORDER=0 ALT="" USEMAP="#KurPhoto_Map">
